Stay at home
Only go outside for food, health reasons or work (but only if you cannot work from home)
If you go out, stay 2 metres (6ft) away from other people at all times
Wash your hands as soon as you get home
Do not meet others, even friends or family.
You can spread the virus even if you don’t have symptoms.

There are currently extremely limited commercial options available to return to the UK from Jamaica.
We know this is concerning for British tourists trying to leave Jamaica. The UK government is working closely with airlines, the Jamaican authorities and other transit country governments to find ways for you to return to the UK when circumstances allow.
Flights
You are encouraged to make indirect travel arrangements via the USA or Canada if possible. You should refer to those countries’ restrictions before travelling to ensure that you will be allowed to enter the country for onward connection.
JetBlue is operating a limited service from Kingston and Montego Bay to Fort Lauderdale. Transfer by bus to Miami International Airport takes 30 minutes. JetBlue also flies from Montego Bay to JFK New York.
The following airlines normally operate direct flights between the UK and Jamaica:
British Airways is advising that the Kingston to London Gatwick route suspension date has been extended to 31 May. This is subject to change. See the British Airways website or call +1 877 767 7970 for more information.
Virgin Atlantic is not currently operating scheduled flights from Montego Bay to London. If you have a booked flight, complete Virgin Atlantic’s Away From Home information.
TUI is not currently operating flights from Jamaica to the UK.
This travel advice will be updated when further departure options become available. Sign up for travel advice email alerts and follow the British High Commission on Twitter and Facebook.
You will need to pay for your return travel to the UK. If departure options are available but you cannot afford the travel costs and have exhausted all other options for getting funds, you may be eligible to apply for an emergency loan from the government. This is a last resort option and you would need to repay the loan when you are back in the UK. For more information, you should contact Corporate Travel Management (CTM). CTM are a commercial partner of the FCO and are authorised to administer such loans on behalf of the FCO.
Your journey home
The National Travel Health Network and Centre (NaTHNaC) provides advice on how to stay safe as you travel by air.
When you arrive back in the UK, follow the guidance for when you return to the UK on steps you should take to protect yourself and others.
If you cannot leave Jamaica
If you cannot leave Jamaica at this time, you should:
follow the advice of local authorities, including local measures to help minimise your risk of exposure to coronavirus and imposition of curfews;
find accommodation that is suitable for your needs;
keep in regular contact with family and friends at home for support and so they know you are safe.
Most hotels for international tourists are no longer open.
See more information and advice about staying where you are if you cannot return to the UK.
Help and support
If you are a tourist in Jamaica and need information and help, you can email the British High Commission at kingston.consular@fco.gov.uk.
If you need urgent consular assistance, you can contact the British High Commission on +1 876 936 0700.
The British High Commission cannot provide further information or advice about departure options over the phone. This page will be updated when departure options become available. To get the latest information, sign up for travel advice email alerts.
